# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: crossroads-kitchen
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] The architects for the original restaurant were Michael Rotondi and Thom Mayne.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] Architectural renovations of the building at 72 Market Street began in 1983, and the restaurant opened its doors for business in August 1984.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] The concept for 72 Market Street originated in Bill and Moore's desire for a casual fine dining eatery in the beachside neighborhood where they both lived.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] 72 Market Street received critical praise for Leonard Schwartz's fare of traditional American “comfort food”.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] A cookbook detailing its recipes, which included portraits of its celebrity patrons and their involvement in the restaurant, was released in 1998.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] A lectures series began in 1985, which featured guests including Spalding Gray, Bill Irwin, Russian poet Yevgeny Yevtushenko, John Hammond Jr., and sleight-of-hand artist Ricky Jay.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] 72 Market Street also partnered with The Paris Review to host an afternoon of readings by authors and poets whose work had been published in their literary review; it including readings by E.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] Coraghessan Boyle, Richard Ford, Tess Gallagher, and Raymond Carver.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] In the late 1980s a live radio program (“Live from 72”) featuring musical entertainment was broadcast live from the restaurant on Sunday evenings on Santa Monica public radio station KCRW.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] Performers on the radio show included Dudley Moore and David Crosby. and featured a trio helmed by house pianist Rafael Nazario.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] In a 2017 post on a Venice Beach community forum, Tony Bill was cited as saying that the restaurant will open in its original place following the closing of Nikkis.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/72-market-street-oyster-bar-and-grill] The same location has a release date of March.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] David Tallichet, a World War II pilot who flew 20 combat missions in a B-17 bomber, founded 94th Aero Squadron under his Specialty Restaurants Corporation, which opened more than 100 restaurants nationwide.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] This restaurant, the first of several under the 94th Aero Squadron banner, was built adjacent to and featured a view of Van Nuys Airport's runway, allowing patrons to watch airplanes take off and land while dining.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] It was named after the 94th Aero Squadron and opened in 1973.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] It was demolished the following year, with plans for an industrial building to rise in its place.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] 94th Aero Squadron's design was said to resemble a French chateau and a rustic Normandy farmhouse.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] A portion of the restaurant was meant to resemble a bombed-out Normandy bunker and one of the restaurant's tables, hand-carved by pilots just after World War II ended, was made of wood from a World War II airplane; in the restaurant, that table was reserved for pilots.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] The restaurant featured numerous military and aviation relics, including a World War I propeller plane, a World War II ambulance, and vintage war Jeeps outside the entrance.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] Inside, memorabilia donated by veterans, including uniforms, gas masks, propellers, torpedoes, and framed photographs, covered the walls and hung from the ceiling.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] Model planes hung from the ceiling as well.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] Additional 94th Aero Squadron restaurants were opened in Chicago, Costa Mesa, Denver, Miami, San Diego, San Jose, St.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] The San Diego chapter of the California Restaurant Association has repeatedly nominated the San Diego location for best American traditional restaurant in the city, and Bill Clinton hosted a meet-and-greet at the St.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/94th-aero-squadron-restaurant] Louis location during his 1992 presidential campaign.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The film opens with footage of a NASA rocket launch, an animation of the Solar System, and a quote from Deuteronomy 30:19 about choosing between life and death (illustrated with images of Earth as seen from space, contrasted with an exploding atom bomb).
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] This is followed by a statement that humanity has not been caring for the planet properly according to Jewish teachings, which precedes a section about ancient Jewish texts and sacred words that provide "specific instructions on how to be custodians of the world in which we live".
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Throughout the film, quotes from the Torah are contrasted with the various environmental threats facing humanity today; the quotes are also illustrated with close-ups of Hebrew scrolls, Jews praying, and scenes of nature.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The Earth is again seen from space and the camera moves in to focus on Israel, which the narrator cites as a microcosm of current global problems related to air and water pollution, overpopulation, climate change, and health concerns.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The film moves on to look at global problems, with scenes shot all over the world.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The focus then shifts to the United States, where all the relevant issues are discussed in detail.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Reference is made to *Livestock's Long Shadow*, a 2006 report by the Food and Agriculture Organization which claimed that livestock agriculture produces more greenhouse gases than all of the world's vehicles combined.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Next comes a brief presentation, illustrated with simple animated charts, on how meat production is an inefficient way to produce food for a hungry world.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] This moves into footage of animal abuse on feedlots and in factory farms, and the pollution produced by these facilities.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The film then focuses on the advantages of vegetarianism for reducing pollution and solving world hunger.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] With a change of diet toward vegetarianism, the film asserts that many of these environmental and health problems can be solved.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] After some fast-moving images of people and nature accompanied by music, the film ends with the same statement from Deuteronomy about "life and death" being narrated over a shot of a sunrise.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The idea for the film was inspired by the writings of Richard H.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz (*Judaism and Vegetarianism*, *Judaism and Global Survival*, etc.) who also served as associate producer.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Schwartz had seen the Christian Vegetarian Association's 2006 film, *Honoring God's Creation*, and felt that a similar film would be effective in the Jewish community.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] At the time, he envisioned the film to be about 30 minutes long, though the final film ended up being 60 minutes long.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Production began in 2005 with a basic proposal and outline in the JVNA's newsletter, along with a statement that Lionel Friedberg was willing to make the film for "a very low fee, basically to cover his costs".
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The film was funded by the JVNA through private contributions.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Preliminary drafts of the script were circulated among members of the JVNA advisory committee and others for input, after which the script went through numerous revisions.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Meanwhile, Schwartz and Friedberg set about interviewing possible participants and filming footage of nature in both Israel and the United States.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] The showing of slaughterhouse footage was controversial, with some members of a test audience in Staten Island seeing it as propaganda.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Friedberg recalled, "Richard and I were accused of making a propaganda film for the vegetarian movement.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] We were accused of showing 'horrors that are impossible to watch'." However, he maintained that the graphic footage was necessary.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] In October and November 2007, *A Sacred Duty* was released direct-to-video and on DVD, with public showings in both Israel and the United States.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Over 35,000 copies were distributed free of charge to synagogues, educational institutions, and individuals, complete with permission to show the film without having to pay the filmmakers any royalties.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] In addition, permission was granted to the public to duplicate and distribute the film free of charge.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/a-sacred-duty] Numerous short excerpts from the film were edited and re-posted by various YouTube users, and the full version became available on YouTube in January 2008.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] Crossroads was opened in 2013 in the Beverly Grove neighborhood by chef Tal Ronnen.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] According to *Los Angeles* magazine, the majority of customers are non-vegan.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In the 2020s the organization opened two additional locations, one in Las Vegas and one in Calabasas, California.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] The restaurant has a Mediterranean focus and a small-plates format.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] Soy foods such as tempeh and tofu are not offered, as soybeans aren't a Mediterranean product.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] Signature dishes include a "seafood" tower and artichoke "oysters".
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] Ronnen also cofounded Kite Hill, a producer of vegan cheeses.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In 2013, Travel + Leisure named Crossroads Kitchen one of the best vegetarian restaurants in the U.S.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] That same year, Patric Kuh of *Los Angeles* magazine critiqued that he wished the restaurant "did more with raw ingredients and, ironically enough, with vegetables," and that the legume dishes lacked inspiration.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In 2014 *Relish* named them one of the 15 best vegan and vegetarian restaurants in the U.S.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In 2015, PETA named them one of the six best vegan fine-dining restaurants in the U.S. and BuzzFeed named them one of 24 "bucket list" vegan restaurants.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In 2017, *Tasting Table* named Crossroads Kitchen one of the eight best vegan restaurants in the U.S. and *The Daily Meal* named them one of the best vegan restaurants in the United States.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In 2018 *USA Today* named them one of the ten best vegan restaurants in the country.
[src:crossroads-kitchen/crossroads-kitchen] In 2019, Big 7 Travel named them one of 50 best vegan-friendly restaurants in the world.
